borrower_name: COLLEGE OF THE MUSCOGEE NATION - TRIBAL GRANT
funding_code: NATIVE AMERICAN TRIBES COMMUNITY FACILITY GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Professional, Scientific, and Technical Services (54)
naics_description: RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT IN THE PHYSICAL, ENGINEERING, AND LIFE SCIENCES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase multi-media equipment for the College of the Muscogee Nations (CMN) new educational facility and exhibit hall, currently under construction on their campus in Okmulgee, Oklahoma. The CMN is a 1994 tribal land-grant institution, providing employment and higher education courses, which result in an associate degree and/or certificates, to 342 Native American staff members, faculty, and students, residing within an eight-county region of central Oklahoma. This project will allow the college to enhance its mission to become a technologically advanced campus. The visibility of the multi-media equipment located throughout the new classrooms and exhibit/lecture hall will create a positive and interactive atmosphere. Use of this multi-media technology will create a greater capacity to host and conduct distance education courses thus enhancing CMNs ability to offer degrees to a wider range of students.

borrower_name: COLLEGE OF THE MUSCOGEE NATION - TRIBAL GRANT
funding_code: NATIVE AMERICAN TRIBES COMMUNITY FACILITY GRANTS
naics_industry_sector: Professional, Scientific, and Technical Services (54)
naics_description: RESEARCH AND DEVELOPMENT IN THE PHYSICAL, ENGINEERING, AND LIFE SCIENCES
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase seating for the College of the Muscogee Nations new lecture hall, currently under construction on their campus in Okmulgee, Oklahoma. In addition, a clock tower will be installed on campus at the Central Circle Plaza. The College of the Muscogee Nation is a 1994 tribal land-grant institution, providing higher education courses resulting in an associate degree and/or a certificate program for their students, along with gainful employment to 459 Native American faculty and staff members, all who reside within an eight-county region of central Oklahoma. This project will allow the college to enhance its mission and provide an area for culture events and student gatherings, as the lecture hall is designed for graduations, science fairs, scholarly presentations, colloquiums, and tribal community meetings.

naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to construct a new spillway on the Waxhoma Dam. The dam is the main water supply for the city of Barnsdall, and due to a heavy rainfall event, the dam was breached in May of 2021. Temporary measures were put in place, but these grant funds will ensure a permanent solution to prevent loss of life and property from failure of the dam, as well as secure the citys water supply.

naics_industry_sector: Agriculture, Forestry, Fishing and Hunting (11)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will assist Miller Pecan Company with working capital allowing them to enter a new market for their one pound packaged Native Pecans. As one of the only producers in the United States that handles their pecans in each step from planting through marketing, this expansion will not only assist them increase their brand awareness, but also attract more distributors and retailers. This project will help develop a rural economy and grow the workforce in Ottawa County.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to provide technical assistance, training, and education to rural areas in all 77 counties of Oklahoma in the field of Solid Waste Management (SWM) by Oklahoma State University. The training will assist participants understand the economic and ecological importance of establishing and implementing SWM programs in their areas.

lender_name: FIRST UNITED BANK AND TRUST COMPANY
funding_code: GUARANTEED B&I 3% FEE LOAN
naics_industry_sector: Arts, Entertainment, and Recreation (71)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to purchase and refurbish a 16-lane bowling facility in McAlester, Oklahoma. The project involves purchasing the building and the 4.5-acre lot, refurbishing the bowling lanes and arcade room, and adding attractions such as cornhole competitions and rentals for specials events. This project will encourage travel to McAlester and create three employment opportunities, keep five local jobs and bring entertainment to the community.

funding_code: RBCS ENTERPRISE NATIVE AMERICAN GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Health Care and Social Assistance (62)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to help create the Good Samaritan Outreach (GSO) community garden center. It will serve as the areas first indoor-aquaponic-garden and community-agriculture training center. GSO will partner with Symbiotic LLC, a Native American-owned business, to construct the aquaponic system and provide aquaponic education and outreach. The goal is to supply homeless men with professional and personal development services while providing the community a year-round source of organic, nutritious, localized, and sustainably produced food.

The project will provide these services for the Tahlequah, Hulbert, Wagoner and Muskogee areas.

funding_code: PILOT BROADBAND GRANT
naics_industry_sector: Utilities (22)
project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to deploy a fiber-to-the-premises network to provide high-speed internet. This network will benefit 1,988 people, 12 businesses and 100 farms in Le Flore County in Oklahoma. Choctaw Nation will make high-speed internet affordable by participating in the Federal Communications Commissions (FCC) Affordable Connectivity Program. This project will serve Choctaw Tribal Statistical Area and socially vulnerable communities in Le Flore County.

The funded service areas include seven educational facilities, 17 critical community facilities, and 867 households spread over 522 square miles.

project_announced_description: This Rural Development investment will be used to develop a 21,300 square foot mental health and substance use disorder treatment clinic. The proposed facility will accommodate up to 26 inpatient beds. It will include nurses stations, exam rooms, detox space, group therapy rooms, seclusion/observation rooms, and a secured medication room. The development of this investment will assist in filling a current void in behavioral healthcare in northcentral Oklahoma.

naics_industry_sector: Educational Services (61)

The program will be operated under the Rural Energy Assessment Center (REAC) at the Mechanical Engineering Technology program of the College of Engineering, Architecture and Technology at Oklahoma State University (OSU).
